The most likely cause is that you never set the page's **`BindingContext`** to your ViewModel. Without it, the `{Binding}` expressions have nothing to resolve against.

**Fix — set the BindingContext** (pick one approach):

**Option A – In code-behind (constructor):**
```csharp
public MyPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = new MyViewModel();
}
```

**Option B – In XAML:**
```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:MyApp.ViewModels"
             ...>
    <ContentPage.BindingContext>
        <vm:MyViewModel />
    </ContentPage.BindingContext>
    ...
</ContentPage>
```

Also verify your ViewModel implements `INotifyPropertyChanged` (or inherits `ObservableObject` from the MVVM Toolkit) so the UI updates when properties change:

```csharp
public class MyViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler? PropertyChanged;

    private string _title = "Hello";
    public string Title
    {
        get => _title;
        set { _title = value; PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new(nameof(Title))); }
    }
}
```

**TL;DR:** No `BindingContext` → bindings resolve to `null` → blank labels.
